result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeffery C. Denton was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Habitual Criminality], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: In the event probation is revoked, Defendant would be entitled to Good Time Credit and Huber Privileges.
The Court would not object to transfer of supervision to the State of New York or any other jurisdiction, provided the appropriate arrangements can be arranged through the Department of Corrections.

miscConds.notes: Court Costs are paid in full from cash bond previously posted.  The balance of the cash bond will be applied to costs imposed as to companion Waushara Co Case No. 2015CF000161.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.

Defendant to complete an Anger Management Program as coordinated by the supervising agent.   Defendant to complete a Domestic Abuse Alternatives Program or its equivalent, together with any follow through counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.  Defendant is also ordered to complete a Parenting Class.    DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.

timeConds.notes: No Good Time Credit and Huber Privileges granted.

15CF-152 and 15CF-161 - Both Cases Called @ 3:37 PM: Defendant Jeffery C. Denton in court with attorney David C. Rashid.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Global resolution recited by DA w/argued terms on sentencing.  Def and counsel concur with State's recital.  15CF-161:  Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty.  Terms of bifurcated SEH explained as to 15CF-161.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  15CF-152 Ct 2 (Battery w/Repeater) Plea:  NC  15CF-161 Ct 1:  NC   Court accepts plea and enters JOC.  Ct Nos 1 and 3 of INFO both DRI.  DA argues as to penalty recommendation.  Argument by Atty Rashid as to penalty recommendation - argues for Good Time component to allow for time served sentence.  In conversations with DOC it is believed that supervision will be able to transfer to State of New York.  Statement by Def:  Yes.  15CF-152:  9 mos WCJ - I/S (GT & Huber if revoked) S/W - 1 yr probation.  120 days WCJ w/97 days TS credit - conditional time.  Conditions:  Anger Mgmt program coordinated by Agent; DAAP or its equivalent; the defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician; Complete a Parenting Class; Court Costs - 60 DTP or PP; DNA Sample and Surcharge Assessed.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice.15CF-161:  S/W - 3 yrs probation w/all conditions ordered in 15CF-152 without conditional jail time being imposed; Court Costs plus DNA Sample and Surcharge.  Court would not object to transferring under interstate compact to the State of New York or any jurisdiction provided the appropriate arrangements are arranged through DOC.   Concurrent terms of supervision.  Appeal Rights Given.
